        'cronGuideTitle' => 'How to Add a Cron Job in cPanel',
        'cronGuideDesc' => 'When you create a new Artisan command that needs to run on a schedule, you need to add it as a cron job in cPanel. Here\'s how:',
        'cronGuideSteps' => [
            'step1' => 'Log in to cPanel (ask your team lead for the cPanel URL and credentials).',
            'step2' => 'Navigate to "Cron Jobs" under the "Advanced" section.',
            'step3' => 'Set the schedule using the minute/hour/day/month/weekday fields. Common patterns: "* * * * *" = every minute, "*/5 * * * *" = every 5 minutes, "0 0,12 * * *" = twice daily at midnight and noon, "0 7 * * *" = daily at 7 AM.',
            'step4' => 'Enter the command in this format: /usr/local/bin/php /home/citycomm/tour.citycommerce.group/artisan YOUR_COMMAND >> /home/citycomm/tour.citycommerce.group/storage/logs/cron/YOUR_LOG_FILE.log 2>&1',
            'step5' => 'The ">> logfile 2>&1" part redirects both normal output and errors to a log file, so you can debug issues later. Always include this.',
            'step6' => 'Click "Add New Cron Job" to save.',
            'step7' => 'Verify by checking the log file after the first expected run: cat /home/citycomm/tour.citycommerce.group/storage/logs/cron/YOUR_LOG_FILE.log',
        ],
        'cronFormatTitle' => 'Cron Schedule Format',
        'cronFormatExample' => "┌───────────── minute (0-59)\n│ ┌───────────── hour (0-23)\n│ │ ┌───────────── day of month (1-31)\n│ │ │ ┌───────────── month (1-12)\n│ │ │ │ ┌───────────── day of week (0-7, 0 and 7 = Sunday)\n│ │ │ │ │\n* * * * *  command\n\nExamples:\n*/3 * * * *     = Every 3 minutes\n0 0,12 * * *    = At midnight and noon\n0 18 * * 0-4    = 6 PM, Sunday to Thursday\n0 7 * * *       = Daily at 7 AM\n* * * * *       = Every minute",
        'cronGuideWarning' => 'Always use the full path to PHP (/usr/local/bin/php) and the full path to the artisan file. Relative paths will not work in cron. Also make sure the storage/logs/cron/ directory exists before adding the cron job.',
        'cronGuideGifPlaceholder' => 'GIF tutorial: How to add a cron job in cPanel (coming soon — will show step-by-step recording of the process)',
    ],

    // Section 8: Jobs & Queue
    'jobs' => [
        'title' => 'Jobs & Queue',
        'desc' => 'Queue jobs handle time-consuming tasks in the background so the user doesn\'t have to wait. For example, sending 50 invoice emails or syncing thousands of hotels from an API would take too long if done in a web request. Instead, these operations are dispatched as jobs that run in the background.',
        'activeTitle' => 'Active Jobs',
        'activeJobs' => [
            'bulkInvoice' => 'CreateBulkInvoicesJob — When a user uploads an Excel file with multiple invoices, each row is validated and then processed by this job. It creates tasks, links them to clients, groups by client and invoice date, creates invoices, and applies any existing payments. Runs on the default queue with 5-minute timeout and 3 retries.',
            'sendInvoice' => 'SendInvoiceEmailsJob — Sends invoice emails with PDF attachments in the background. When you click "send invoice" in the UI, this job is dispatched so the user doesn\'t have to wait for the email to actually be sent. Retries 3 times with backoff of 10/30/60 seconds.',
            'syncCountries' => 'SyncCountriesJob — Syncs country data from the Magic Holiday API. Dispatched by the mapping:sync command. Runs on the "api_sync" queue with 5-minute timeout.',
            'syncCities' => 'SyncCitiesJob — Syncs cities for a specific country from the Magic Holiday API. One job is dispatched per country. Runs on the "api_sync" queue with 10-minute timeout.',
            'syncHotels' => 'SyncHotelsJob — Syncs hotels for a specific city from the Magic Holiday API. One job is dispatched per city. This is the most data-intensive sync job.',
            'updateMagicDates' => 'UpdateMagicHolidayIssuedDateJob — Updates the issued_date for hotel tasks from the Magic Holiday API. Runs on the "magic_holiday_updates" queue with 1-minute timeout.',
            'syncGateway' => 'SyncGatewayMethods — A dispatcher job that determines which payment gateway sync service to call (MyFatoorah, UPayment, or Hesabe) and executes the appropriate sync.',
        ],
        'queueTitle' => 'Queue Configuration',
        'queueDesc' => 'The system uses the DATABASE queue driver in production — jobs are stored in the "jobs" table and processed by queue workers. There are two named queues: "default" (for general jobs like invoice emails) and "api_sync" (for API synchronization jobs). Set QUEUE_CONNECTION=database in .env for production. For local development, use QUEUE_CONNECTION=sync so jobs execute immediately without needing a queue worker. To run the queue worker: php artisan queue:work --tries=3. The scheduler also runs: php artisan queue:work --queue=api_sync --stop-when-empty every minute to process API sync jobs.',
        'failedTitle' => 'Failed Jobs',
        'failedDesc' => 'When a job fails after all retry attempts, it\'s moved to the "failed_jobs" table. Check failed jobs with: php artisan queue:failed. Retry a specific job: php artisan queue:retry {id}. Retry all: php artisan queue:retry all. Always investigate WHY a job failed before retrying — check storage/logs/laravel.log for the error.',
    ],

    // Section 9: Payment Gateways
    'payments' => [
        'title' => 'Payment Gateway Integration',
        'desc' => 'The system integrates with 5 payment gateways for online payment collection. Each gateway has its own API, callback mechanism, and fee structure. Companies can configure different gateways with different credentials.',
        'gatewaysTitle' => 'Supported Gateways',
        'gateways' => [
            'tap' => 'Tap Payment — Primary gateway for credit/debit card payments. Supports Visa, Mastercard, and Apple Pay. Config: TAP_SECRET_KEY, TAP_PUBLIC_KEY. Gateway class: app/Support/PaymentGateway/TapGateway.php.',
            'myfatoorah' => 'MyFatoorah — Multi-method payment gateway popular in Kuwait and the Gulf region. Supports Knet, Visa, Mastercard, Apple Pay, and more. Payment methods are synced daily. Config: MYFATOORAH_API_KEY, MYFATOORAH_COUNTRY_ISO.',
            'hesabe' => 'Hesabe — Kuwait-based gateway with direct Knet support. Uses a custom encryption service (HesabeCrypt) for request/response encryption. Config: HESABE_API_KEY, HESABE_MERCHANT_CODE, HESABE_SECRET.',
            'upayment' => 'UPayment — Multi-method gateway supporting Knet, credit cards, Samsung Pay, and more. Config: UPAYMENT_API_KEY, UPAYMENT_MERCHANT_ID.',
            'knet' => 'Knet — Direct integration with Kuwait\'s national payment network (bank transfers). Config: KNET_TRANSPORT_ID, KNET_PASSWORD, KNET_RESOURCE_KEY.',
        ],
        'architectureTitle' => 'Architecture',
        'architectureDesc' => 'Payment gateway classes are in app/Support/PaymentGateway/. Each gateway implements a consistent interface for: (1) initiating a payment session, (2) redirecting the client to the gateway\'s payment page, (3) handling the callback/webhook when payment completes, (4) verifying the payment status. The GatewayConfigService retrieves the correct API credentials based on the company.',
        'callbackTitle' => 'Payment Callbacks',
        'callbackDesc' => 'Each gateway sends a callback (webhook) to our system after payment. The PaymentController handles these callbacks: it verifies the payment with the gateway, updates the payment record, applies the payment to the invoice, creates accounting journal entries, and sends a confirmation email. Callback routes are defined in routes/web.php.',
        'perCompanyTitle' => 'Per-Company Configuration',
        'perCompanyDesc' => 'Each company has its own payment gateway credentials stored (encrypted) in the database. This allows multi-tenant payment processing — Company A can use Tap while Company B uses MyFatoorah, each with their own merchant accounts. The admin panel has a settings page where companies configure their gateway credentials.',
    ],

    // Section 10: GraphQL API
    'graphql' => [
        'title' => 'GraphQL API',
        'desc' => 'The system uses the Lighthouse package to provide a GraphQL API alongside the standard REST routes. GraphQL allows frontend clients to request exactly the data they need in a single query.',
        'schemaTitle' => 'Schema Location',
        'schemaDesc' => 'The GraphQL schema is defined in graphql/schema.graphql. It defines types (Task, Invoice, Client, etc.), queries (fetching data), and mutations (creating/updating data). Each type maps to an Eloquent model. Custom resolvers are in app/GraphQL/.',
        'endpointTitle' => 'Endpoint',
        'endpointDesc' => 'GraphQL endpoint: POST /graphql. In local development, you can use GraphQL Playground at /graphql-playground to test queries interactively. This playground is disabled in production for security.',
        'authTitle' => 'Authentication',
        'authDesc' => 'GraphQL requests require authentication via Bearer token. Protected queries use the @guard(with: "sanctum") directive in the schema. Unauthenticated requests to protected queries return a 401 error.',
    ],

    // Section 11: Email & Communication
    'email' => [
        'title' => 'Email & Communication',
        'desc' => 'The system both sends and receives emails. Outgoing emails are used for invoices, payment links, and notifications. Incoming emails are processed by AI to automatically extract booking information.',
        'outgoingTitle' => 'Outgoing Emails (Mailables)',
        'outgoingDesc' => 'All email templates are Mailable classes in app/Mail/. Each Mailable has a corresponding Blade view in resources/views/emails/. Key mailables:',
        'mailables' => [
            'invoiceMail' => 'InvoiceMail — Sends the invoice to the client with a PDF attachment. Triggered when an agent clicks "Send Invoice" or via AutoBilling.',
            'paymentLink' => 'PaymentLinkEmail — Sends a payment link that the client can click to pay online. The link takes them to a page where they choose a payment gateway.',
            'paymentMail' => 'PaymentMail — Payment confirmation/receipt sent after successful payment. Includes the receipt voucher PDF.',
            'autoBillMail' => 'AutoBillMail — Notification sent when AutoBilling creates an invoice automatically. Informs the agent/client that an invoice has been generated.',
            'bulkInvoice' => 'BulkInvoicesMail — Notification after a bulk invoice upload is processed. Reports how many invoices were created and any errors.',
            'reminderMails' => 'UninvoicedTaskReminderMail, UnassignedTaskReminderMail — Automated reminders sent to agents about tasks that need attention (see Cron Job Commands section).',
            'verification' => 'SendVerificationCodeMail — Sends a verification code for password reset. Contains a 6-digit code that expires after a set time.',
            'notification' => 'NotificationMail — General-purpose notification email template used for various system notifications.',
        ],
        'incomingTitle' => 'Incoming Email Processing',
        'incomingDesc' => 'The system reads incoming emails via IMAP (webklex/php-imap) from specific Gmail labels (magic, tbo, webbeds). The ReadAndProcessEmails command fetches these emails, then sends the content to OpenAI for structured data extraction. The AI identifies booking references, hotel names, dates, guest names, and pricing. This data is used to create or update task records. This process automates what would otherwise be manual data entry from supplier confirmation emails.',
        'imapTitle' => 'IMAP Configuration',
        'imapDesc' => 'Configure IMAP in .env: IMAP_HOST (usually imap.gmail.com), IMAP_PORT (993), IMAP_ENCRYPTION (ssl), IMAP_USERNAME, IMAP_PASSWORD. For Gmail, you need to enable IMAP access and use an App Password (not your regular Gmail password). The email reading is used by the emails:process command which runs every 10 minutes.',
    ],

    // Section 12: File Processing
    'fileProcessing' => [
        'title' => 'File Processing (PDF & Air Files)',
        'desc' => 'The system processes several types of files: AIR files (airline booking data), PDFs (generating invoices and receipts), Excel files (bulk imports/exports), and scanned documents (OCR). Understanding AIR file processing is especially important because it\'s one of the main ways bookings enter the system.',
        'pdfTitle' => 'PDF Generation',
        'pdfDesc' => 'PDF documents are generated server-side for invoices, payment receipts, and reports. The system uses multiple PDF libraries depending on the complexity of the document:',
        'pdfLibraries' => [
            'dompdf' => 'DomPDF — Primary PDF engine. Converts Blade HTML templates to PDF. Used for standard invoices and receipts. Simple but limited in positioning control.',
            'tcpdf' => 'TCPDF — Used for complex PDF layouts that need precise positioning (e.g., ticket layouts). More powerful but harder to work with than DomPDF.',
            'fpdi' => 'FPDI — Manipulates existing PDF templates. Used when you need to fill data into a pre-designed PDF form.',
            'mergepdf' => 'libmergepdf — Merges multiple PDFs into one document. Used when generating a combined PDF of all invoices for batch printing.',
            'pdfToImage' => 'spatie/pdf-to-image — Converts PDF pages to images. Used for preview thumbnails.',
            'pdfParser' => 'smalot/pdfparser — Extracts text from uploaded PDFs. Used when processing supplier documents.',
        ],
        'airTitle' => 'AIR File Processing',
        'airDesc' => 'AIR (Airline Inventory Record) files are text-based documents exported from GDS systems (like Amadeus) that contain flight booking data. When an agent books a flight, the GDS generates an AIR file. Our system automatically reads and parses these files to create Task records. This is one of the primary ways flight bookings enter the system.',
        'airServices' => [
            'parser' => 'AirFileParser (app/Services/AirFileParser.php) — The core parser that reads raw AIR file text and extracts structured data: ticket numbers, passenger names, flight segments (departure/arrival airports, dates, times), pricing (fare, tax, surcharge), airline/GDS references, and booking status (issued, voided, refunded, exchanged).',
            'service' => 'AirFileService (app/Services/AirFileService.php) — Orchestrates the import process. Takes the parsed data from AirFileParser, normalizes it using TaskSchema/TaskFlightSchema, matches agents and suppliers, and creates the Task and TaskFlightDetail records in the database.',
            'command' => 'ProcessAirFiles command (app:process-files) — The cron job command that runs every 3 minutes. Scans the air-files directory, processes each file using AirFileParser and AirFileService, then moves processed files to an archive folder. Uses locking to prevent overlapping runs.',
        ],
        'ocrTitle' => 'OCR & Vision',
        'ocrDesc' => 'The system has Tesseract OCR and Google Cloud Vision integration for extracting text from scanned documents and images. This is used when agents upload photos or scans of receipts and booking confirmations that need to be processed into task data.',
        'excelTitle' => 'Excel Processing',
        'excelDesc' => 'Excel import/export is handled by Maatwebsite Excel (laravel-excel). Main uses: (1) Bulk Invoice Upload — users upload an Excel file with multiple bookings, validated by BulkInvoiceValidationService, then processed by CreateBulkInvoicesJob. (2) Chart of Accounts Import — importing a company\'s COA from Excel. (3) Report Exports — exporting sales reports, agent commission reports, etc. to Excel format for download.',
    ],

    // Section 13: AI Integration
